Here are the public test cases for feature1_broadcast_and_return:
{
  "description": "A logging facade broadcasts every log call to all registered sinks and returns the value that was logged. Each call carries a severity level (informational message, warning, fatal, or error) and a payload (a text message, or for the error level an exception value). When one or more sinks are registered, issuing a call delivers that call to each sink in registration order and yields back the original payload unchanged. The output reports, per call in the order issued, a line with the returned payload, followed by one line for each sink that received the call, naming the sink, the severity level, and the delivered payload.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "log",
        "clients": [
          "A"
        ],
        "calls": [
          {
            "level": "message",
            "message": "Message"
          },
          {
            "level": "warning",
            "message": "Warning"
          },
          {
            "level": "fatal",
            "message": "Fatal"
          },
          {
            "level": "error",
            "exception": "Error"
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "return=Message\nclient=A level=message message=Message\nreturn=Warning\nclient=A level=warning message=Warning\nreturn=Fatal\nclient=A level=fatal message=Fatal\nreturn=Error\nclient=A level=error exception=Error\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "log",
        "clients": [
          "A",
          "B"
        ],
        "calls": [
          {
            "level": "message",
            "message": "Message"
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "return=Message\nclient=A level=message message=Message\nclient=B level=message message=Message\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature2_except_for:
{
  "description": "When issuing a log call, specific sinks can be excluded by their kind so the call is not delivered to them, while every other registered sink still receives it and the logged value is still returned. The exclusion list names sink kinds to skip; a sink whose kind is excluded receives nothing at all for that call. The output reports the returned payload followed by one line for each sink that actually received the call; excluded sinks contribute no line. This works the same way across all severity levels.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "log",
        "clients": [
          "A",
          "B"
        ],
        "calls": [
          {
            "level": "message",
            "message": "Message",
            "exceptFor": [
              "B"
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "return=Message\nclient=A level=message message=Message\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature3_1_message:
{
  "description": "A colorizing sink renders an informational log entry as a single line with no color treatment. The line consists of an uppercase level tag in square brackets, a single space, and the original message text, terminated by a newline.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "colorize",
        "level": "message",
        "message": "Service started"
      },
      "expected_output": "[MESSAGE] Service started\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature3_2_warning:
{
  "description": "A colorizing sink renders a warning log entry as a single line wrapped in ANSI SGR escape sequences for a black foreground over a yellow background. The line begins with the color-activation sequences, then an uppercase level tag in square brackets, a space, the message text, and finally the reset sequence, terminated by a newline. The foreground is xterm color index 0 and the background is xterm color index 3; each is introduced with the escape byte (0x1B), an opening bracket, the SGR selector, and is closed by the reset sequence (escape byte, opening bracket, zero, lowercase m).",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "colorize",
        "level": "warning",
        "message": "Low disk space"
      },
      "expected_output": "\u001b[38;5;0m\u001b[48;5;3m[WARNING] Low disk space\u001b[0m\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature3_3_fatal:
{
  "description": "A colorizing sink renders a fatal log entry as a single line wrapped in ANSI SGR escape sequences for a white foreground over a red background. The line begins with the color-activation sequences, then an uppercase level tag in square brackets, a space, the message text, and finally the reset sequence, terminated by a newline. The foreground is xterm color index 7 and the background is xterm color index 1.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "colorize",
        "level": "fatal",
        "message": "Out of memory"
      },
      "expected_output": "\u001b[38;5;7m\u001b[48;5;1m[FATAL] Out of memory\u001b[0m\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature3_4_error:
{
  "description": "A colorizing sink renders an error log entry as a single line wrapped in ANSI SGR escape sequences for a bold white foreground over a dark-red background. The payload is composed from an exception value and a stacktrace value laid out as a structured fragment: an uppercase level tag in square brackets, a space, then an opening brace, the labeled exception value, a comma, the labeled stacktrace value, and a closing brace. The whole fragment is wrapped between the color-activation sequences and the reset sequence, terminated by a newline. The foreground is xterm color index 15 and the background is xterm color index 88.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "colorize",
        "level": "error",
        "exception": "Connection refused",
        "stacktrace": "at socket.connect"
      },
      "expected_output": "\u001b[38;5;15m\u001b[48;5;88m[ERROR] { exception: Connection refused, stacktrace: at socket.connect }\u001b[0m\n"
    }
  ]
}
